body:
@ewencp Yeah, I started in that direction, resolving the references just using `ConnectSchema` before finishing the build, but ran into a few issues. The `ConnectSchema` also sets it's key and value schemas  as final in the constructor, so patching them up afterwards when it's an array or map would need us to be flexible on that `final` as well. But the blocking issue was that once the schema is built,  doing `.equals` or `.hashcode` causes a loop. The `FutureSchema` knows to break the hashing/equals loop. I have since thought of some scenarios where the current logic will not work as desired (for example starting a comparison with the `FutureSchema` as root), but have fix in progress (WIP until then).

In regards to the access of `FutureSchema`, I think you are correct that it shouldn't be visible outside the `SchemaBuilder`.  I now understand that the optional and default fields are related to the 'instance' of a type rather than the definition of the type. Which category are `parameters` in?

I think extending the `SchemaBuilder` with a `private FutureSchemaBuilder` that only allows setting `optional` and `default` (maybe `parameters`?) clean up the API. Thoughts?
